String Method in Javascript with Examples
=========================================

1. concat():

This method is used to combine two or more strings and return a new string. The original strings remain unchanged.

let string1 = " I Love ";
let string2 = "Javascript";
let result = string1.concat(string2); // "I Love Javascript"


2. includes():

This method checks whether a string contains a specified substring and returns a boolean value, 
true if the string contains the substring and false if it doesn't

let string = "I Love Javascript";
let result = string.includes("Love"); // true

3. split():

This method divides a string into an ordered list of substring, puts these substring into an arry, and returns the array.

let string = "I Love Javascript";
let result = string.split(" "); // ["I", "Love", "Javascript"]

4. replace():

This method returs a new string with a replacement for some or all of the pattern matches.

let string = "I Love Javscript";
let result = string.replace("Love" , "Adore");


5. replaceAll():
 
This method returns a new string with a replacement for each match of a pattern. 

let string = "I Love Javascript, I Really Do!"
let result = string.replaceAll("I", "We")

6. trim():

This method removes whitespace from both ends of a string. whitespace in this context is all the whitespace characters (space, tab, no-break space, ete..)
and all the line terminator characters.

let string = " I Love Javascript ";
let result = string.trim(); //"I Love Javascript";

7. toUpperCase():

This method returns the calling string value converted to toUpperCase.

let string = "I Love Javascript";
let result = string.toUpperCase(); //"I LOVE JAVASCRIPT"

8. toLowerCase():

This method returns the calling string value converted to toLowerCase. So, "I Love JavaScript" turns into "i love javascript"

let string = "I LOVE JAVASCRIPT";
let result = string.toLowerCase(); //"i love javascript"

9. .charAt():

REturn the character at a speific index.

let string = "abc";
strring.charAt(1); //b

10. .includes():

Checking if a string contains a specified value.
let str = "Hello"
str.includes(el); //true

11. .indexOf():
REturn the index of the first occurance of a value
let str = 'Hello';
str.indexOf(e); // 1

12. .slice();
Extracts a part of a string
 let str = "Hello"; 
 str.slice(1,3) ; //"el"




